   =20
      Shareholder democracy
   =20
 =20

A decent first cut is that shareholder voting doesn=E2=80=99t matter. That=
=E2=80=99s not completely right or anything. Sometimes there are things =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0proxy fights, controversial mergers,=20
new share issuances for meme stocks =E2=80=94=C2=A0where the shareholder vo=
te really matters. But for almost every US public company, almost every yea=
r, the things that come up for votes are:
=09Director elections, which seem like they would matter, but don=E2=80=99t=
. The director elections are almost always uncontested; you can either vote=
 for the incumbent directors, or you can vote=C2=A0against=C2=A0them and fo=
r nobody else. If a majority of the shares are voted against a director, th=
en she will probably have to resign from the board, though not always, but =
in any case she=E2=80=99ll be replaced by another director chosen by the ot=
her incumbent directors. It=E2=80=99s not like the shareholders vote every =
year on whether or not to fire the board or the chief executive officer.=09=
Nonbinding advisory proposals on things like executive pay, environmental i=
nitiatives, governance stuff, etc., where if a majority of shareholders vot=
e against management=E2=80=99s recommendation then that is embarrassing but=
 nothing really happens.

The shareholders almost never vote on anything=C2=A0binding; in the ordinar=
y course, they have no real power to choose the managers or strategy of the=
 company.
Now of course this is not=C2=A0entirely=C2=A0true, and I spend a lot of tim=
e around here on   the mechanisms for transforming shareholder dissatisfact=
ion into binding shareholder action to remove the managers of the company. =
But it is=C2=A0mostly=C2=A0true, so that there are roughly three ways to be=
 a public-company shareholder:
  [1]

=09Be an=C2=A0activist, and=C2=A0specialize=C2=A0in taking or threatening b=
inding shareholder action. =E2=80=9CIf you don=E2=80=99t implement my strat=
egy I will run a proxy fight and fire the directors,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CI=
 will mount a hostile tender offer and buy the whole company and fire the d=
irectors.=E2=80=9D This is a specialized niche, and there are not a whole t=
on of investors in this business, but we   talk about them a   lot because =
they are=C2=A0important. They are the mechanism for turning shareholder dis=
satisfaction into binding action. When shareholders are mad at a company=E2=
=80=99s managers, when they vote against management on nonbinding proposals=
, an activist will see an opportunity and come in to try to make a change. =
A decent first cut is that shareholder voting doesn=E2=80=99t matter, but a=
ctivism is the way to make it matter.=09Try to influence managers through i=
ndirect channels. Meet with the managers, tell them what you want, and impl=
y that if they ignore you then you will vote against them in nonbinding dir=
ector elections, which will embarrass them, and which might attract an acti=
vist, who might run a proxy fight, and you might vote for the activist. The=
 managers will want to keep a good reputation, and they will want to keep t=
he risk of a proxy fight as low as possible, so they will meet with their b=
ig shareholders and try to keep them happy, and this approach can work.=C2=
=A0=09Just don=E2=80=99t care about any of this. Buy stock in companies tha=
t you think are well managed, don=E2=80=99t buy stock in companies that you=
 think are poorly managed, and don=E2=80=99t kid yourself that you can do a=
nything about the management.

For individual retail investors, the third approach is always the rational =
approach. For big institutional investors, particularly the very biggest, t=
he second approach is tempting. You are a fiduciary for your clients, and w=
hile you=C2=A0mostly=C2=A0exercise your fiduciary duties by picking stocks,=
 it seems not-quite-fiduciary to=C2=A0ignore=C2=A0shareholder voting. Also =
the very biggest institutions run a lot of index-fund money, so they=C2=A0c=
an=E2=80=99t=C2=A0sell the companies that they think are mismanaged, so the=
y might as well try to influence them. Also, big institutions are in the bu=
siness of marketing themselves to clients, and saying =E2=80=9Cwe encourage=
 our companies to do good things=E2=80=9D might be better marketing than sa=
ying =E2=80=9Cwe never meet with companies, what=E2=80=99s the point.=E2=80=
=9D This is often bound up with environmental, social and governance invest=
ing: For a while, at least, ESG was good marketing, so it helped asset mana=
gers to be able to say =E2=80=9Cwe meet with companies and tell them to pol=
lute less,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwe vote for good governance proposals.=E2=
=80=9D
But there has been a backlash, not just to ESG but to the general idea that=
 big asset managers should influence companies. The companies=E2=80=99 mana=
gers don=E2=80=99t love it, for one thing; they=E2=80=99d rather not have s=
hareholder pressure. US Republicans don=E2=80=99t love it, because they thi=
nk that the big asset managers have liberal social values and will influenc=
e companies to be too =E2=80=9Cwoke.=E2=80=9D There is   a belief that thes=
e asset managers are=C2=A0too=C2=A0big, and that their influence creates an=
titrust trouble: If all of the companies are owned by the same three giant =
firms, won=E2=80=99t they be tempted to collude? And clients might disagree=
 with some of the asset managers=E2=80=99 decisions, and want to vote their=
 shares their own way.
One obvious solution is for the asset managers to let their clients do thei=
r own voting: If a big asset manager owns 1 million shares of a company for=
 its clients, it can poll the clients on how they want to vote, and then vo=
te its shares however the clients say. If the clients are too busy to respo=
nd, the asset manager can decide how to vote the shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0or t=
he clients can opt in to some pre-set voting rules. The rules might be =E2=
=80=9Calways vote however management wants us to,=E2=80=9D but they might a=
lso defer to some third party. =E2=80=9CAlways vote how some shareholder pr=
oxy advisory service tells us to.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CHire an ESG consultant =
and always vote the way they tell us to.=E2=80=9D
Here=E2=80=99s the latest from BlackRock Inc., a letter from Larry Fink tit=
led =E2=80=9C The transformative power of choice in proxy voting=E2=80=9D:

Today, we believe that choice can and should extend, not just to the strate=
gies in which clients invest, but also to how clients engage in the governa=
nce of companies their money is ultimately invested in. At BlackRock, we=E2=
=80=99re doing this through what we call Voting Choice: a capability that l=
everages technology and innovation to give our clients =E2=80=93 who are th=
e true owners of the assets we manage =E2=80=93 the option to engage much m=
ore directly in proxy voting. =E2=80=A6
We=E2=80=99ve seen tremendous interest from our clients since launching a y=
ear ago. Nearly half of all our index equity assets under management are no=
