10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Shareholder democracy</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A decent first cut is that shareholder voting =
doesn=E2=80=99t matter. That=E2=80=99s not completely right or anything. So=
metimes there are things =E2=80=94=C2=A0proxy fights, controversial mergers=
, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29584608.276473/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjQvYW1=
jLXMtYXBlcy1taWdodC1zdGljay1hcm91bmQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEwMzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdX=
RtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTAzJnV0b=
V9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB90310adb" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">
new share issuances for meme stocks</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0where the shareholde=
r vote really matters. But for almost every US public company, almost every=
 year, the things that come up for votes are:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Director elections, which seem like th=
ey would matter, but don=E2=80=99t. The director elections are almost alway=
s uncontested; you can either vote for the incumbent directors, or you can =
vote=C2=A0<em>against=C2=A0</em>them and for nobody else. If a majority of =
the shares are voted against a director, then she will probably have to res=
ign from the board, though not always, but in any case she=E2=80=99ll be re=
placed by another director chosen by the other incumbent directors. It=E2=
=80=99s not like the shareholders vote every year on whether or not to fire=
 the board or the chief executive officer.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">Nonbinding advisory proposals on things like executive pay, enviro=
nmental initiatives, governance stuff, etc., where if a majority of shareho=
lders vote against management=E2=80=99s recommendation then that is embarra=
ssing but nothing really happens.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The shareholders almost never vote on anything=
=C2=A0<em>binding</em>; in the ordinary course, they have no real power to =
choose the managers or strategy of the company.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now of course this is not=C2=A0<em>entirely=C2=
=A0</em>true, and I spend a lot of time around here on <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29584608.276473/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb2=
1iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMjcvZXh4b24tbG9zdC1hLWNsaW1hd=
GUtcHJveHktZmlnaHQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEwMzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFp=
bCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTAzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25=
leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe6da6276" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  the mechanisms for t=
ransforming shareholder dissatisfaction into binding shareholder action</a>=
 to remove the managers of the company. But it is=C2=A0<em>mostly=C2=A0</em=
>true, so that there are roughly three ways to be a public-company sharehol=
der:<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: t=
ransparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Be an=C2=A0<em>activist</em>, and=C2=
=A0<em>specialize=C2=A0</em>in taking or threatening binding shareholder ac=
tion. =E2=80=9CIf you don=E2=80=99t implement my strategy I will run a prox=
y fight and fire the directors,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CI will mount a hostile=
 tender offer and buy the whole company and fire the directors.=E2=80=9D Th=
is is a specialized niche, and there are not a whole ton of investors in th=
is business, but we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/29584608.276473/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMjItMDMtMjQvdGhlLXNlYy13YW50cy10by1zdG9wLWFjdGl2aXNtP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMDMy=
Ml9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV9=
0ZXJtPTIyMTEwMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBae=
8419df" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">  talk</a> about them a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/29584608.276473/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMjcvY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS1naXZlcy1maXJzdC1ib3N0=
b24tZ2V0cy1hLXNlY29uZC1jaGFuY2U_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEwMzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21=
lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTAzJnV0bV9jYW=
1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB949e4fc9" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  lot</a>=
 because they are=C2=A0<em>important</em>. They are the mechanism for turni=
ng shareholder dissatisfaction into binding action. When shareholders are m=
ad at a company=E2=80=99s managers, when they vote against management on no=
nbinding proposals, an activist will see an opportunity and come in to try =
to make a change. A decent first cut is that shareholder voting doesn=E2=80=
=99t matter, but activism is the way to make it matter.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">Try to influence managers through indirect channels. =
Meet with the managers, tell them what you want, and imply that if they ign=
ore you then you will vote against them in nonbinding director elections, w=
hich will embarrass them, and which might attract an activist, who might ru=
n a proxy fight, and you might vote for the activist. The managers will wan=
t to keep a good reputation, and they will want to keep the risk of a proxy=
 fight as low as possible, so they will meet with their big shareholders an=
d try to keep them happy, and this approach can work.=C2=A0</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Just don=E2=80=99t care about any of this. Buy st=
ock in companies that you think are well managed, don=E2=80=99t buy stock i=
n companies that you think are poorly managed, and don=E2=80=99t kid yourse=
lf that you can do anything about the management.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For individual retail investors, the third app=
roach is always the rational approach. For big institutional investors, par=
ticularly the very biggest, the second approach is tempting. You are a fidu=
ciary for your clients, and while you=C2=A0<em>mostly=C2=A0</em>exercise yo=
ur fiduciary duties by picking stocks, it seems not-quite-fiduciary to=C2=
=A0<em>ignore=C2=A0</em>shareholder voting. Also the very biggest instituti=
ons run a lot of index-fund money, so they=C2=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em=
>sell the companies that they think are mismanaged, so they might as well t=
ry to influence them. Also, big institutions are in the business of marketi=
ng themselves to clients, and saying =E2=80=9Cwe encourage our companies to=
 do good things=E2=80=9D might be better marketing than saying =E2=80=9Cwe =
never meet with companies, what=E2=80=99s the point.=E2=80=9D This is often=
 bound up with environmental, social and governance investing: For a while,=
 at least, ESG was good marketing, so it helped asset managers to be able t=
o say =E2=80=9Cwe meet with companies and tell them to pollute less,=E2=80=
=9D or =E2=80=9Cwe vote for good governance proposals.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there has been a backlash, not just to ESG=
 but to the general idea that big asset managers should influence companies=
. The companies=E2=80=99 managers don=E2=80=99t love it, for one thing; the=
y=E2=80=99d rather not have shareholder pressure. US Republicans don=E2=80=
=99t love it, because they think that the big asset managers have liberal s=
ocial values and will influence companies to be too =E2=80=9Cwoke.=E2=80=9D=
 There is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29584608=
.276473/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMTI=
tMDcvcmVndWxhdG9ycy1hc2staWYtaW5kZXgtZnVuZHMtYXJlLWJhZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTAzMj=
JfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fd=
GVybT0yMjExMDMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe3f=
cdc68" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">  a belief</a> that these asset managers are=C2=A0<em>too=C2=
=A0</em>big, and that their influence creates antitrust trouble: If all of =
the companies are owned by the same three giant firms, won=E2=80=99t they b=
e tempted to collude? And clients might disagree with some of the asset man=
agers=E2=80=99 decisions, and want to vote their shares their own way.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One obvious solution is for the asset managers=
 to let their clients do their own voting: If a big asset manager owns 1 mi=
llion shares of a company for its clients, it can poll the clients on how t=
hey want to vote, and then vote its shares however the clients say. If the =
clients are too busy to respond, the asset manager can decide how to vote t=
he shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0or the clients can opt in to some pre-set voting r=
ules. The rules might be =E2=80=9Calways vote however management wants us t=
o,=E2=80=9D but they might also defer to some third party. =E2=80=9CAlways =
vote how some shareholder proxy advisory service tells us to.=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=9CHire an ESG consultant and always vote the way they tell us to.=E2=80=
=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s the latest from BlackRock Inc.,=
 a letter from Larry Fink titled =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/29584608.276473/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxhY2tyb2NrLmNvbS9=
jb3Jwb3JhdGUvYWJvdXQtdXMvaW52ZXN0bWVudC1zdGV3YXJkc2hpcC9ibGFja3JvY2stdm90aW=
5nLWNob2ljZS9wcm94eS12b3RpbmctcG93ZXItb2YtY2hvaWNl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B438406b4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> The transformative power of choice in proxy voting</a>=
=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Today, we believe that choice can and should e=
xtend, not just to the strategies in which clients invest, but also to how =
clients engage in the governance of companies their money is ultimately inv=
ested in. At BlackRock, we=E2=80=99re doing this through what we call Votin=
g Choice: a capability that leverages technology and innovation to give our=
 clients =E2=80=93 who are the true owners of the assets we manage =E2=80=
=93 the option to engage much more directly in proxy voting. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We=E2=80=99ve seen tremendous interest from ou=
r clients since launching a year ago. Nearly half of all our index equity a=
ssets under management are now eligible for Voting Choice. This includes al=
l the public and private pension plan assets we manage in the United States=
, as well as retirement plans serving more than 60 million people around th=
e world. To date, clients representing 25% of the $1.8 trillion in eligible=
 assets are enrolled in Voting Choice, and interest is only accelerating: T=
he number of clients interested in enrolling has doubled since May.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s clear there are investors who don=
=E2=80=99t want to sit on the sidelines; they have a view on corporate gove=
rnance, and they want a meaningful way to express those views. While some p=
ension funds have long been actively involved in corporate governance, we=
=E2=80=99re working to make that easier and more efficient for a larger num=
ber of investors. We are committed to continually evolving this offering.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the anniversary of its launch, we are expan=
ding Voting Choice further: by extending the pool of eligible client assets=
 that can participate, expanding the range of voting guidelines from which =
clients can choose, and working to bring this capability to individual inve=
stors in select mutual funds in the United Kingdom. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We believe that voting choice can empower more=
 asset owners to have a deeper and more direct connection to the companies =
they are invested in and allow company management to better understand the =
views of these asset owners on critical governance issues. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This revolution in shareholder democracy will =
take years to be fully realized, but it is one that, if executed correctly,=
 can strengthen the very foundations of capitalism.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/29584608.276473/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZ=
XdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDIvdmFuZ3VhcmQtdG8tdGVzdC1naXZpbmctcmV0YWlsLWlu=
dmVzdG9ycy1tb3JlLXZvdGluZy1wb3dlcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTAzMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1=
fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjExMDMmdXRtX2=
NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9943b747" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Bloo=
mberg News reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Vanguard Group is planning a trial to give ret=
ail clients more say over how their shares are voted at corporate meetings,=
 as large money managers=E2=80=99 influence over hot-button issues faces mo=
unting scrutiny.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead of making decisions exclusively on its=
 own, Vanguard will give individual investors in several equity index funds=
 more options about how their shares are voted, the Valley Forge, Pennsylva=
nia-based company said Wednesday in a statement. It will begin testing the =
strategy early next year.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can read these things as basically express=
ive. Clients =E2=80=94=C2=A0pensions, individuals =E2=80=94=C2=A0want to de=
cide how to vote their shares, because they have values, and want to vote t=
o express their values. But=C2=A0<em>the votes don=E2=80=99t matter</em>. S=
hareholder voting mostly does not have the power to tell companies what to =
do. There=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>mechanisms for shareholders to tell compan=
ies what to do, but they tend to rely on concentration and bigness. If Blac=
kRock says =E2=80=9Cwe own 10% of your company and if you don=E2=80=99t do =
what we want we will find an activist who will,=E2=80=9D companies have to =
take that seriously.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But now BlackRock kind of can=E2=80=99t say th=
at anymore? =E2=80=9CWe own 10% of your company but we don=E2=80=99t vote t=
hose shares, our clients do, and they=E2=80=99re all over the place.=E2=80=
=9D The result of this is likely to be=C2=A0<em>less shareholder power:=C2=
=A0</em>The shareholders are more dispersed, and they=C2=A0<em>pay less att=
ention:=C2=A0</em>BlackRock bought all that stock for them; they=E2=80=99re=
 just voting.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is probably what a lot of people want! If=
 you think that shareholder power is bad =E2=80=94=C2=A0for antitrust or wo=
ke-capital reasons, or because you are a CEO and <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29584608.276473/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDgtMTkvbWF4aW1pemUtc2hhcmVob2xkZXItdmF=
sdWUtdG9wLWNlb3MtbWlnaHQtYmUtb3B0aW5nLW91dD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTAzMjJfTU9ORVlTVF=
VGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjExM=
DMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB68d4d357" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">find shareholders annoying</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0then having less sharehold=
er power is a good result. But I am not sure it is a revolution in sharehol=
der democracy.</p>
